ame":"Caunton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Taunton in Somerset. The place takes its name from the river Tone (the name of which is related to the Indo-European root <i>tā-</i>, <i>tə-</i> ‘melt, flow’) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Tanton","meanings":["English (mainly Devon and Kent): variant of   Taunton  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan de Caunton was born in 1309, in Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1309–":"1309–Surnud","1309–1335":"1309–1335","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1335–1368":"1335–1368","1309–Female":"1309–Surnud","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1300":"1300","1309":"1309","Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Caunton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Youlton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Youlton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1309–":"1309–Kuollut","1309–1335":"1309–1335","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1335–1368":"1335–1368","1309–Female":"1309–Kuollut","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1300":"1300","1309":"1309","Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Caunton, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Youlton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Youlton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1309–":"1309–Décédée","1309–1335":"1309–1335","1300–Male":"1300–Décédé","1335–1368":"1335–1368","1309–Female":"1309–Décédée","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1300":"1300","1309":"1309","Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Caunton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Youlton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Youlton, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Joan de Caunton est née en 1309, à Caunton, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1309–":"1309–Verstorben","1309–1335":"1309–1335","1300–Male":"1300–Verstorben","1335–1368":"1335–1368","1309–Female":"1309–Verstorben","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1300":"1300","1309":"1309","Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Caunton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Youlton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Youlton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Joan de Caunton wurde 1309 in Caunton, Nottinghamshire, Engla